    <h2 id="vaginal-microbiome">The Vaginal Microbiome: Why Strain-Specific Probiotics Matter</h2>

    <p>The vaginal microbiome is fundamentally different from the gut microbiome. In healthy women, the vaginal environment is dominated by Lactobacillus species — particularly <em>L. crispatus</em>, <em>L. iners</em>, <em>L. gasseri</em>, and <em>L. jensenii</em> — that maintain an acidic pH between 3.8 and 4.5. This acidic environment is the primary defense mechanism against pathogenic organisms including Gardnerella vaginalis (bacterial vaginosis), Candida albicans (yeast infections), and Escherichia coli (urinary tract infections).</p>

    <p>When Lactobacillus dominance is disrupted — by antibiotics, hormonal fluctuations, sexual activity, douching, or stress — vaginal pH rises above 4.5, creating conditions favorable for pathogenic overgrowth. This is where vaginal probiotic gummies play a critical role: specific Lactobacillus strains taken orally travel through the gut and colonize the vaginal tract via the <strong>gut-vaginal axis</strong>, restoring the protective acidic environment. However, not all probiotic strains perform this migration — only clinically validated strains have demonstrated the ability to reach and colonize vaginal mucosa after oral supplementation.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
