      <div class="info-card"><div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="heart" size={22} /></div><strong>L. reuteri RC-14</strong><p>Partners with GR-1 to restore Lactobacillus dominance. Produces lactic acid and biosurfactants that prevent pathogenic biofilm formation. The GR-1 + RC-14 combination reduced BV recurrence by 51% in a 2019 meta-analysis published in the European Journal of Obstetrics &amp; Gynecology.</p></div>
      <div class="info-card"><div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="flask" size={22} /></div><strong>L. crispatus</strong><p>The dominant Lactobacillus species in healthy vaginal flora. Produces the highest concentration of lactic acid among vaginal Lactobacillus species, maintaining the lowest and most protective pH. Women with L. crispatus-dominant flora have the lowest rates of BV and STI acquisition.</p></div>
      <div class="info-card"><div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="droplet" size={22} /></div><strong>L. acidophilus</strong><p>A well-studied strain that maintains acidic vaginal pH (3.8-4.5) through lactic acid production. Also produces hydrogen peroxide and bacteriocins — antimicrobial compounds that directly kill pathogenic bacteria. Found in many commercially available vaginal probiotic formulas.</p></div>
    </div>

    <div class="callout">
      <p><strong>Clinical evidence:</strong> A 2019 meta-analysis in the <em>European Journal of Obstetrics &amp; Gynecology and Reproductive Biology</em> analyzed 14 randomized controlled trials and found that <strong>oral probiotics containing Lactobacillus reduced bacterial vaginosis recurrence by 51%</strong> compared to placebo. The strongest results were observed with the L. rhamnosus GR-1 + L. reuteri RC-14 combination taken daily for at least 4 weeks.</p>
      <cite>Jeng et al., European Journal of Obstetrics &amp; Gynecology and Reproductive Biology, 2019</cite>
    </div>

